04164nam a22006975i 9780226464589DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2017    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264645897 a10.7208/97802264645892doi  a(DE-B1597)522729  a(OCoLC)979417599  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPN49b.M53 2018 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a401223  aEC 18202rvk1 aMoi, Toril, eauthor.10aRevolution of the Ordinary :bLiterary Studies after Wittgenstein, Austin, and Cavell /cToril Moi. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4cÂ©2017  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Wittgenstein -- tPart II. Differences -- tPart III. Reading -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis radically original book argues for the power of ordinary language philosophy-a tradition inaugurated by Ludwig Wittgenstein and J. L. Austin, and extended by Stanley Cavell-to transform literary studies. In engaging and lucid prose, Toril Moi demonstrates this philosophy's unique ability to lay bare the connections between words and the world, dispel the notion of literature as a monolithic concept, and teach readers how to learn from a literary text. Moi first introduces Wittgenstein's vision of language and theory, which refuses to reduce language to a matter of naming or representation, considers theory's desire for generality doomed to failure, and brings out the philosophical power of the particular case. Contrasting ordinary language philosophy with dominant strands of Saussurean and post-Saussurean thought, she highlights the former's originality, critical power, and potential for creative use. Finally, she challenges the belief that good critics always read below the surface, proposing instead an innovative view of texts as expression and action, and of reading as an act of acknowledgment. Intervening in cutting-edge debates while bringing Wittgenstein, Austin, and Cavell to new readers, Revolution of the Ordinary will appeal beyond literary studies to anyone looking for a philosophically serious account of why words matter.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCriticism. 0aLanguage and languagesxPhilosophy. 0aLiteraturexPhilosophy. 0aOrdinary-language philosophy. 4aFerdinand de Saussure. 4aJ. L. Austin. 4aJacques Derrida. 4aLudwig Wittgenstein. 4aStanley Cavell. 4aacknowledgment. 4aattention. 4ahermeneutics of suspicion. 4aintersectionality. 4aordinary language philosophy. 4arealism. 70(DE-601)1041959590(DE-588)4194196-2aTextanalyse2gnd 70(DE-601)1061546720(DE-588)4056486-1aSprachphilosophie2gnd 70(DE-601)1062450150(DE-588)4035964-5aLiteratur2gnd 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226464589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226464589.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles